                    "group_id": "V-220663",
                    "severity": "low",
                    "group_title": "The Cisco switch must have IGMP or MLD Snooping configured on all VLANs.",
                    "rule_id_src": "SV-220663r929005_rule",
                    "rule_id": "SV-220663r929005",
                    "rule_version": "CISC-L2-000170",
                    "rule_title": "The Cisco switch must have IGMP or MLD Snooping configured on all VLANs.",
                    "fix_text": "Configure IGMP or MLD snooping for IPv4 and IPv6 multicast traffic respectively globally.\n\nSW1(config)#ip igmp snooping",
                    "weight": "10.0",
                    "check_content": "Review the switch configuration to verify that IGMP or MLD snooping has been configured for IPv4 and IPv6 multicast traffic respectively. Below is an example of the steps to verify that IGMP snooping is enabled for each VLAN.\n\nStep 1: Verify that IGMP or MLD snooping is enabled globally. By default, IGMP snooping is enabled globally; hence, the following command should not be in the switch configuration: \n\nno ip igmp snooping\n\nStep 2: Verify that IGMP snooping is not disabled for any VLAN as shown in the example below:\n\nno ip igmp snooping vlan 11\n\nNote: When globally enabled, it is also enabled by default on all VLANs, but can be disabled on a per-VLAN basis. If global snooping is disabled, VLAN snooping cannot be enabled. \n\nIf the switch is not configured to implement IGMP or MLD snooping for each VLAN, this is a finding.",
                    "check_content_ref": {
                        "href": "Cisco_IOS_XE_Switch_L2S_STIG.xml",
                        "name": "M"
                    },
                    "classification": "Unclassified",
                    "discussion": "IGMP and MLD snooping provides a way to constrain multicast traffic at Layer 2. By monitoring the IGMP or MLD membership reports sent by hosts within a VLAN, the snooping application can set up Layer 2 multicast forwarding tables to deliver specific multicast traffic only to interfaces connected to hosts interested in receiving the traffic, thereby significantly reducing the volume of multicast traffic that would otherwise flood the VLAN.",
                    "false_positives": "",
                    "false_negatives": "",
                    "documentable": "false",
                    "security_override_guidance": "",
