                    ],
                    "group_id": "V-220670",
                    "severity": "medium",
                    "group_title": "The Cisco switch must not use the default VLAN for management traffic.",
                    "rule_id_src": "SV-220670r991907_rule",
                    "rule_id": "SV-220670r991907",
                    "rule_version": "CISC-L2-000240",
                    "rule_title": "The Cisco switch must not use the default VLAN for management traffic.",
                    "fix_text": "Configure the switch for management access to use a VLAN other than the default VLAN.\n\nSW1(config)#int vlan 22\nSW1(config-if)#ip add 10.1.22.3 255.255.255.0\nSW1(config-if)#no shut",
                    "weight": "10.0",
                    "check_content": "Review the switch configuration and verify that the default VLAN is not used to access the switch for management.\n\ninterface Vlan22\n description Management VLAN\n ip address 10.1.22.3 255.255.255.0\n\nIf the default VLAN is being used for management access to the switch, this is a finding.",
                    "check_content_ref": {
                        "href": "Cisco_IOS_XE_Switch_L2S_STIG.xml",
                        "name": "M"
                    },
                    "classification": "Unclassified",
                    "discussion": "Switches use the default VLAN (i.e., VLAN 1) for in-band management and to communicate with directly connected switches using Spanning-Tree Protocol (STP), Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP), VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP), and Port Aggregation Protocol (PAgP)—all untagged traffic. As a consequence, the default VLAN may unwisely span the entire network if not appropriately pruned. If its scope is large enough, the risk of compromise can increase significantly.",
                    "false_positives": "",
