                    "group_id": "V-220671",
                    "severity": "medium",
                    "group_title": "The Cisco switch must have all user-facing or untrusted ports configured as access switch ports.",
                    "rule_id_src": "SV-220671r991908_rule",
                    "rule_id": "SV-220671r991908",
                    "rule_version": "CISC-L2-000250",
                    "rule_title": "The Cisco switch must have all user-facing or untrusted ports configured as access switch ports.",
                    "fix_text": "Disable trunking on all user-facing or untrusted switch ports.\n\nSW1(config)#int g0/6\nSW1(config-if)#switchport mode access\nSW1(config-if)#end",
                    "weight": "10.0",
                    "check_content": "Review the switch configurations and examine all user-facing or untrusted switchports. The example below depicts both access and trunk ports.\n\ninterface GigabitEthernet0/1\n switchport trunk encapsulation dot1q\n switchport mode trunk\n negotiation auto\n!\ninterface GigabitEthernet0/2\nswitchport access vlan 11\n negotiation auto\n!\ninterface GigabitEthernet0/3\n switchport access vlan 12\n negotiation auto\n\nIf any of the user-facing switch ports are configured as a trunk, this is a finding.",
                    "check_content_ref": {
                        "href": "Cisco_IOS_XE_Switch_L2S_STIG.xml",
                        "name": "M"
                    },
                    "classification": "Unclassified",
                    "discussion": "Double encapsulation can be initiated by an attacker who has access to a switch port belonging to the native VLAN of the trunk port. Knowing the victim's MAC address and with the victim attached to a different switch belonging to the same trunk group, thereby requiring the trunk link and frame tagging, the malicious user can begin the attack by sending frames with two sets of tags. The outer tag that will have the attacker's VLAN ID (probably the well-known and omnipresent default VLAN) is stripped off by the switch, and the inner tag that will have the victim's VLAN ID is used by the switch as the next hop and sent out the trunk port.",
                    "false_positives": "",
                    "false_negatives": "",
                    "documentable": "false",
                    "security_override_guidance": "",
                    "potential_impacts": "",
